  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>EVERQUEST : HIS RISE - CHAPTER 1</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><center><b>Chapter One</b><br><i>An Attack, scouts, and a mage</i></center><p>
     Cries filled the air, and trumpets blasted. Men in armor ran towards the front gates, swords drawn. The commotion of the town woke all, boys ran the streets calling all to arms. An attack from the gnoll’s was approaching. The routine, however, was common enough. Most even stayed in their houses, claiming that if it were bad enough they would do more protecting their families than to laugh at the clumsy gnolls and their unplanned attacks.<p> 
     Truly, it was a sight to see. In no order they would charge, barking their lungs out. Yet, barking was all most of them would ever do, for the Qeynos Arrow Guard picked them off from a rather safe distance. This was how most of the gnoll attacks had been stopped, most didn’t even consider it an attack, only a “trainee scrimmage”. Officers even hoped for a gnoll attack to train their soldiers how to combat semi-smart opponents. Even though most gnolls lacked the ‘smartness’ needed.<p>
     None the less, guards ran and men gathered at the west gates. Slowly, the noise dropped from a loud joyous cries of the coming battle, to a somber state of silence. Men gazed over and far into the hills, only to see gnolls. Hundreds of gnolls, in set formations, in one section of lines a flag bearing the Sabertooth’s of Black Burrow insignia waved in the night air. Across to the other side, another flag waved, to a non traveler this would be an odd sign, but to a battle worn veteran it was the sign of Paw. A division of gnolls within the Karana’s, yet their clan for the most part was wiped out some time ago, by the center division.<p>
     Amassing the largest of the three armies, rode the battle standard of the Tesch Clan, all divided into it’s subjugate divisions, with the Ishva leading in the fore. At this distance, none could tell their exact numbers, but all knew, this was a major attack. Gathering three of the largest gnoll clans for an assault upon the human land of Qeynos. The air seemed to freeze, and breaths were held. Even the oldest veterans held on tightly to their blades at the sight. A sight that could very well be their lasts.<p>
     Breaking the silence, a man’s voiced boomed through the crowd of onlookers. The commander of the Steel Blades pushed his way though the group of men and stared too at the on coming gnolls. For a second, one would have said his eyes widened, but if they did it happened to quick to notice. Taking a deep breath, he walked a few yards in front of the gates and turned toward’s the men.<p>
     “Brother’s of Qeynos! Our time has come this day, to prove to Norrath that we are able to stand our foothold of Antonica! Our fellow brother’s of Freeport have held off those Drows for years, and we too will defeat this threat of ours,” called Ebon Strongbear as he hefted his fist into the night air, which was responded to by various cries in the crowd. Not satisfied, he continued.<p>
     “Since I was recruited, I have fought these beasts many times. I have seen then fall and I have seen them kill those who lived within the walls. I have lived long enough since the Battle of Trexx to see that they have stayed back long enough,<p>
     “Their attack now, will be there last!” Cries sprung into the air, accompanied by claps of battle, of wants.<p>
     “And with their last attack, Qeynos will be free of all of the accursed beasts for many years to come, so be it under Antonious Bayle!” Adding to the drama, he hefted his sword high into the air, and brought it’s blade point down into the ground, until it was sunken to mid length within the dirt. Cries for their king went up into the night air, cries of battle rumbled among the walls.<p>
     Ebon gave a small smirk and made his way back through his men, to where his messengers should be waiting with reports. Reports he should have gotten a long time before now. As he entered a small area within the gates, he glanced over to the small booth where the messengers liked to wait and drink. He found none. <p>
     Walking further into the room, he found a small note on the table. Picking it up, he frowned as it read:<p><i>
Ebon,<p>
     I have taken Milor to the Clerics Of Life, he was badly hurt by some spell. He had begun to cough up blood while clutching his stomach. Not sure what had happened, figured the clerics would know what to do. <p>
     As for me, I ran back out for Tiethroe. While on his run back he was attacked by a band of gnolls. I saw the fight from a distance, he dropped two, but six more were after him. Perhaps, I will get there in time to save him, I know where he’d hide given the situation. At that note, I’m off.<p>
Your Trusted Halfling,<br>
Sekerv <p></i>
     Crumpling up the note, he threw it back onto the table and walked out of the room at a pace which would have knocked any in his way aside. The cleric’s enclave was just a few blocks away, to find a patient however, could be a little more difficult and time consuming. Yet, to find Milor, the accursed rogue would probably be hiding from anything bearing the sign of an alien god. Chuckling at the matter a little, his hopes raised, Milor was a good scout and a well trained rogue. Not one to up and quit.<p>
     Yet, Sekerv had mentioned, magic. Gnoll’s wielded magic? Thinking back to the formation of the oncoming assault, he figured someone in there should know the art. But, gnolls? They didn’t do anything but bark and holler, while being picked off by arrows from the ramparts. Magic was not a matter of his, he knew how to resist it, not fight against it or with it. That was the Hall’s matter. A matter, he would have to bring up, and quickly.<p>
     Approaching the teleport into the Cleric’s Enclave, he stepped before the pedestal. Glancing about, he noticed no one standing around, no one offering prayers to the gods. No one. Guessing most must have ran into the parade of troops, or were hiding within the walls of the enclave. Perhaps, they had all ran home to protect their families or say their good byes, for a war was just over the hills.<p>
     Reciting a quick word, given to leaders of the city, he felt a twirling feeling. So were such things when stepping through a teleport. Much worse, when stepping into a gate. The world stopped spinning around him, as he gained his bearings. Glancing about, the halls were about the same as he had last left them. Their tall blue walls reached high above the head, with pennants and flags bearing Rodcet Nife lined them. Within the center of the room roared the Life’s Flame.<p> 
     The building, which he stood in now, was said to be the eye of Rodcet Nife himself. It levitated just above the Life’s Fire, as it drowned itself into a cool crystal pool. A pool where the only Kolandi would ever be, for the fish needed the pure water of life to survive. Ebon remembered swimming in the pond as a child, and staring up into the flame. There had been no heat, and as he gazed up, a huge rotating ‘eye’ had been over him. The vision froze in his head, and from that moment on, he had secretly served Rodcet Nife, betraying the normal war gods.<p>
     Within the ‘Eye’, a cleric’s power was raised. Granted, they served the Giver of Life. It was one of the few relics which had withstood many attacks. As it was believed to be sent down by Rodcet himself as a sign of his love for his followers. At the time, all believers of the Life were being killed, so the god took them up into his own ‘watch’ and granted them power within his sight. The below pond, were the tears of a god, and some continue to say, they still are.<p>
     The air hummed with radiant power, as a clear aroma filled Ebon’s nostrils. Wandering around upon the blue carpet he soon found a young cleric walking quickly around the building.<p>
     “Servant of Life,” Ebon called as he began to trot in her direction.<p>
     “Milor is within the High Priest’s offices. You’ll find them there, sir,” she responded without even slowing her pace or looking back at him. She had just known. Puzzled by this, he stopped his walk and turned in the direction of the High Priest’s offices. Who was it that he was supposed to meet there, why was he meeting ‘them’?<p>
     As he approached the door, it opened on it’s own accord. Halting a quick instant, he reached for the hilt of his sword. In front of the door way, stood an man dressed in robes, enchanted robes, not the normal clerical dress for these parts. Meeting the Swordmaster’s hand at his hilt with a raised eye brow, the man looked up into Ebon’s eyes.<p> 
     “Well, it’s always good to see a fellow human rush into the High Priest’s office with his sword drawn like a crazed troll, don’t you think Tonmerk?” stated the man in the robes, as he backed away from the door. Giving access for Ebon to enter, the man just smiled at him.<p> 
     Stepping into the room, the swordmaster eyed the man in the dark draped robes. Not wanting to remove his hand from his sword’s hilt. For a moment, Ebon felt as if he was being prodded by magic, but not in the normal sense. He was unsure what he was feeling, but knew it had to do something with this man before him, just smiling. However, his attention was pulled away when he saw the Priest of Life approach.<p>
     “Ah, Ebon Strongbear, it’s always a pleasure to have you here. Very few Steel Warriors serve Nife these days,” stated the man within his clerical robes, as he gave the swordmaster a gentle pat on the back.<p>
     “Long life to ye High Priest Tonmerk,” Ebon replied, dropping his arms to his side. Now more relaxed that his old friend was beside him, and not just some wizardly looking dark man.<p>
     “Oh, please, you flatter me Ebon,” Tonmerk barked into the air, as he then followed it with a chuckle. “So, I presume you have come to me, to retrieve your scouts?”<p>
     “Aye, are all three here?” Ebon once again shifted his gaze to the new face to his mind, and then back to the priest.<p>
     “Three? I have received two,” the priest looked a bit concerned, and turned towards the man beside the door, “did you see any others out there, or only the one you brought in?”<p>
     The man in the robes nodded as if thinking to himself, then chuckled, as if remembering something. Ebon didn’t see any joke in the matter, and to have his scouts laughed at by some stranger, raised the heat in his head. <p>
     “What did you do with my scouts!” Ebon withdrew two blades from his sides, and held them before the mage. Holding them both in a cross before his face, a Steel Warrior’s warning sign of danger, and most often soon coming death.<p>
     The air sizzled as the swords met some unseen barrier, but the swordmaster did not withdraw. Anger flashed in Tonmerk’s eyes, as a hammer flashed in seconds into his hand, and slammed down Ebon’s twin blades. Shock was easily seen in the swordmaster’s eyes.<p>
     “There will be no blood shed within my temple. Not even if you believe you have a just cause Ebon, and in your case, you do not. So sit down and listen to the man, he was the one who saved two of your scouts,” slowly the righteous anger within the priest’s eyes died down, and resumed their normal, calm appeal.<p>
     Taking a short bow to Tonmerk, Ebon sheathed both blades at his side. Slowly realizing how this rotating made his chain armor feel heavier, but that didn’t matter. It was too petty of a matter to complain about, he had to listen to the mage speak of what evil’s he had done to his scouts.v
     “Excuse my assumptions, mage. The day has not been the best and I got a city soon to be under attack, and then I found out my most trusted scouts were injured and one ran off after another,” going on and on Ebon stated his case, until the mage held up a hand and smiled at the swordmaster. Ebon liked that smile for some reason, since he had fist seen it, it seemed to calm him, to overtake him. It had to be magic.<p>
     “No apologies needed Swordmaster Ebon, you concern and dilemma are both understandable,” giving a quaint bow to the swordmaster, he continued with that same smile always at the corner of his lips.<p>
     “First, I should introduce myself. I am Simonic Dul’Khar, a wanderer of the lands. This day the good gods put me in the path of, I know now, your scouts. While surveying the progress of the gnoll’s, which I had been keeping watch over their advancement for some time, about three weeks. I noticed a pair of men fighting a rather large group of gnolls,<p>
     “I ran at a gentle pace up to the area in which the fight was taking place, from what I could see at the time, there was a halfling, his armor soaked with gnoll blood. And a half elf, who seemed to be badly injured but still fought as if he wasn’t.”<p>
     Ebon smiled at the picture, it seemed all too much like Tiethroe. Noticing that the mage had stopped his tale because of his appearance, he motioned the mage to continue. In which, he gently tilted his head and continued on with the story.<p>
     “Ah, well between the two of them, twenty two gnolls were on their backs and stomach’s either dead or soon to be. Yet, twenty were still on top of them and another group was running up to them from the south. The halfling seemed to be fine, and his skill was of the likes I had never seen. A rather good compliment for him Swordmaster Ebon,<p>
     “Yes, well I glanced at the surrounding areas and figured they could use my aid. I then began casting Mesm –– I began casting various spells, in which turned out to turn the battle for your scouts, and I was able to help the half elf here,”<p>
     Ebon glanced up, taking in the story and then asked, “that’s it?”<p>
     “Ebon, show your manners before him within my temple!” Declared the Priest, who too was listening.<p>
     Simonic raised his hand as to wave off an assault, “his concerns are expected, and no that is not it. The halfling stated he was well, and wanted to continue his patrol. He said the elf would be able to report to you what has been happening out there. I then, was asked if I could bring him here. Keeping my word, I did,” that accursed smile came once again to the mage’s lips as he finished his tale, as he found a small granite bench to rest on within the Priest’s Office.<p> 
     Ebon was the one to return the smile, and bowed before the mage, “you have my thanks Simonic Dul’Khar, and may the Life be granted unto you,” turning towards Tonmerk, his smile faded, “may I see my scouts, please friend?”<p>
     Tonmerk gave a low tilt of his head, and led Ebon to a back room. Within the center of the room, were two tiers. Both shone with a brilliant light, upon one was the crumpled form of Milor and the other held a battered form of Tiethroe. Ebon walked up alongside Milor’s tier and inspected the small elf’s form. For the most part, it appeared that the blood had stopped flowing from his mouth, due to the effects of some spell. But, in no way did he look up for scouting any time soon, the spell had seemed to suck the life from the poor elf, shriveling his form.<p>
     Moving a few steps in the opposite direction he glanced over Tiethroe’s form. Ebon’s eyes just about watered. It was just that, a mangled form of one of his best scouts. However, he didn’t see any blood flowing, and for the most part, life was fully in him, but the deep gashes in various sections of his body, made it almost unable for him to move a muscle. A small smile came to the lips of the half elf.<p> 
     “Eb...on, how...are..ye,” just those simple words seemed to take their tole on the Tiethroe, yet not once had he lost his smile. A smile for battle.<p>
     Ebon held his finger in front of his mouth, to hush the injured elf. Tiethroe simply twitched his head in a twitch which appeared to resemble a nod of agreement. His eyes closed, and was soon breathing the slow rhythmic breaths of one in sleep. Tonmerk came alongside him, and glanced down at Tiethroe as well. <p>
     “He’s shown a great improvement over the past couple hours, though it does make me wonder about that mage,” the priest pressed the palm of his hand gently upon the forehead of the elf and said a soft prayer. Soon Tiethroe’s body was encased in a shimmering case. A spell granted to only the High Priest of Rodcet Nife, and within the boundaries of the ‘eye’, it’s potency elevated a great deal.<p>
     “The man, Simonic?” Ebon lifted his head from gazing at the shimmering encasing and looked into the priest’s eyes, “I didn’t find anything utterly wrong with him, though at first I did have my doubts.”<p>
     Tonmerk gave a quick glance at the swordmaster’s blades on his side belt and grinned, “you seemed to have more doubts about him than I,” under the quick ridicule of the priest, he blushed. “Ah, no worries friend, imagine how you would feel if you were resting in your chambers when there’s a knock at the door<p>
     “It’s not a thing I’m totally used to, specially when I opened it I was greeted by a complete stranger,” Tonmerk turned from Tiethroe’s body and headed over to a small padded cushion, which was being elevated by some unseen force.<p>
     Slowly, he sat in it, and let out a long breath. This was the first time Ebon saw his friends age showing. The man was getting older, already nearing nearly sixty seasons. The thought made him shudder, he was approaching his forty second season soon himself. The priest wore a long white robe, with gold lace running from the neck to the bottom skirt. Upon his waist, a thick belt of gold rested rather loosely, and hanging from there, was the Hammer of Nife.<p> 
     A grand hammer, given only to the High Priest, and only able to be wielded by him. Or whoever was the high priest at the current time. Yet, many have concluded that Tonmerk is it’s best care taker, and uses it justly. Other than those few items he wore, the priest stayed fairly casual within his enclave. The rumors of his ‘hermit’ life style were true, for he had not left the enclave for more than twenty seasons. Some even claimed him to be dead, or to be along side Nife in the heavens. Ebon knew better than to believe tavern tales of his friend.<p>
     “Ye had never met the man before –– how did he gain entrance to the Enclave?”<p>
     Tonmerk shrugged at the question and simply smiled, “I figured only Servants of Nife could enter the temple, let alone pass by the warding magics guarding my offices,” standing from his cushion he returned alongside Tiethroe’s body and glanced through the still shimmering case.<p> 
     “What I find strange is how he casted his magic,” Tonmerk made a few gestures and the casing around Tiethroe’s body fell, falling to the ground in an airy facade, “he used, healing magic alongside the spells of an Enchanter,” again his hands began to move in circles above Tiethroe’s head as he recited an incantation.<p> 
     “Are ye saying he is more than just a regular wizard or enchanter?” Ebon’s attention was once again caught, as if it had wandered much of anywhere lately, other than the plans of an attack that the gnoll’s could possibly possess.<p> 
     “I am saying, he <i>is</i> more than an enchanter and wizard. He can heal a great deal of wounds -- and if it were not for the gashes of Tiethroe’s body, I would say he received a Spell of Completeness, or to some a Complete Heal” finishing his earlier incantation a blue haze drifted over the elf’s body and it convulsed, taking in a deep breath.<p> 
     “I am not saying we need to worry, but he wields something no other Member of the Hall wields.”<p>
     Ebon knew what he had meant. The Hall of Sorcery only allowed initiates to study one school of magic, and in no way could they learn healing magics. Those were specifically reserved for the clerics and paladins. Once again, the importance of contacting the Hall spurred into his head. But, first they must have a conversation with an eye witness, Tiethroe. <p>
<center>
**********************************************<p>
<b>Chapter Two</b><br><i>A Healing. A Battle. The Mages.</i></center><p>
     Tiethroe took another deep gulp of air, his lips regaining their dark reddish color. A trait among various half elves. Another blue haze went over the elf as Tonmerk continued his castings. Ebon knew that healing process, each wave brought an inexplicable joy, from cold darkness to warm godly light. The breath of inhaling brought one out of the trance, and the deep gulp was due because most resisted taking the breath, so they might enjoy the bliss for a few moments longer.<p>
<center><b><i>...more to come...</i></b></center> </font></td>
